Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 34th Weekly Dose of Optimism. What a w=
eek, huh? It=E2=80=99s been one for the history books, filled with low lows=
 and high highs.=20
Last Friday, we mentioned the struggles at Silicon Valley Bank. Later that =
morning, the FDIC took over and uncertainty reigned until the US government=
 stepped in and backstopped deposits on Sunday night. In the process, the t=
ech industry managed to piss a whole lot of people off.=20
And then=E2=80=A6 we got the easiest week ever to write about optimistic th=
ings. GPT-4, Midjourney v5, space manufacturing, TikTok bans, delivery dron=
es. Whiplash.=20
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
The Weekly Dose is brought to you by=E2=80=A6Masterworks [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/422f2a40-fb04-4ad8-b463-9=
b1c16ed85c0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
I don=E2=80=99t own much great physical art, other than a set of vibrant Ta=
kashi Murakami prints that a friend gave to me. I can=E2=80=99t afford the =
good stuff. But on the internet, I own paintings by Basquiat, Haring, Warho=
l, and even Picasso. Well, I own shares in those paintings at least, thanks=
 to Masterworks [ https://substack.com/redirect/422f2a40-fb04-4ad8-b463-9b1=
c16ed85c0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ].
I=E2=80=99ve been working with Masterworks [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
422f2a40-fb04-4ad8-b463-9b1c16ed85c0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] for years, and personally investing with the=
m the entire time. In the beginning, before they=E2=80=99d sold any of the =
pieces they=E2=80=99d purchased, I just thought it was a really cool way to=
 access an inaccessible and less correlated asset class while beautifying m=
y portfolio. Over the past year, though, they=E2=80=99ve begun selling work=
s in the portfolio for a gain. In fact, every single one of Masterworks=E2=
=80=99 11 exits [ https://substack.com/redirect/422f2a40-fb04-4ad8-b463-9b1=
c16ed85c0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ] to date has returned a profit to their investors, totaling more than $3=
0 million in payouts.=C2=A0Pretty, pretty good!
They=E2=80=99re proving out their thesis: that art can perform well even wh=
en other assets don=E2=80=99t.=C2=A0A majority of those sales weren=E2=80=
=99t in the go-go era of =E2=80=9Ceverything goes up=E2=80=9D, meme stocks,=
 and bitcoin at 60k=E2=80=A6 each one was sold for a gain, even during time=
s of soaring inflation and finical market plummets.
New offerings are launching every week, and tend to sell out fast. But as a=
 longtime partner I=E2=80=99ve secured some VIP passes to skip their waitli=
st at the Not Boring link:
(1) GPT-4 [ https://substack.com/redirect/36d4412f-8645-427f-9caa-e1d65332c=
799?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From OpenAI
We=E2=80=99ve created GPT-4, the latest milestone in OpenAI=E2=80=99s effor=
t in scaling up deep learning. GPT-4 is a large multimodal model (accepting=
 image and text inputs, emitting text outputs) that, while less capable tha=
n humans in many real-world scenarios, exhibits human-level performance on =
various professional and academic benchmarks.
We=E2=80=99re not sure if you heard, but OpenAI released GPT-4 this week. E=
arly reports indicate that people are able to do some cool stuff with it:
By all accounts, GPT-4 is a marked improvement over GPT-3.5. If you like ke=
eping up with the daily ins-and-outs of AI developments, we recommend subsc=
ribing to Ben Tossell=E2=80=99s [ https://substack.com/redirect/8b45efcb-fc=
e9-4826-a1b8-572bcf23b748?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] newsletter Ben=E2=80=99s Bites [ https://substack.com/r=
edirect/6e756c6e-3ec6-48ca-bf34-1db8dba880f7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7=
GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
(2) U.S. Threatens Ban if TikTok=E2=80=99s Chinese Owners Don=E2=80=99t Sel=
l Stakes [ https://substack.com/redirect/a6e23e37-fe44-4a31-b7b8-eb6b18cc32=
f6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
John D. McKinnon [ https://substack.com/redirect/6c64853c-43e7-4ae7-b194-bd=
4937042acd?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ] for The Wall Street Journal
The Biden administration is demanding that TikTok=E2=80=99s Chinese owners =
sell their stakes in the video-sharing app or face a possible U.S. ban [ ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/e266d9cf-5fe6-4d36-88f5-0e45359d1291?j=3DeyJ1Ij=
oiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] of the app, acco=
rding to people familiar with the matter.
Finally. We have long been proponents of U.S. regulation of TikTok, and it =
looks like the Biden Administration is now going to force the sale of TikTo=
k in the U.S.
As Alec Stapp put it on Twitter [ https://substack.com/redirect/bc7910c3-c9=
f9-4afc-a6ef-b2e18cb9c959?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]: =E2=80=9CWe would never have allowed the Soviet Union =
to control programming on CBS, NBC, or ABC during the Cold War. Same applie=
s to TikTok and the CCP.=E2=80=9D For better or worse, we are in the beginn=
ings of the Second Cold War, and this time our adversary is the CCP.
We=E2=80=99re not warmongers. We=E2=80=99re not geopolitical experts. I dee=
ply wish that both the U.S. and China could be less zero-sum in their appro=
ach to all of this. That being said, it makes zero sense that the U.S. allo=
ws TikTok (in it=E2=80=99s current form) to operate in the U.S. My argument=
 isn=E2=80=99t tit-for-tat: just because Meta and Google can=E2=80=99t oper=
ate in the China, doesn=E2=80=99t mean that TikTok shouldn=E2=80=99t be abl=
e to operate in U.S. My argument is more objective: our primary adversary c=
ontrols the most powerful social technology in our country, and said advers=
ary has a long track record of using powerful technologies to spy and manip=
ulate on certain groups of people. It just doesn=E2=80=99t make sense.
Is the U.S. forcing TikTok to sell an optimistic story? Maybe not. But is i=
t a story that American=E2=80=99s should feel very positively about? Absolu=
tely.
(3) The Vesuvius Challenge [ https://substack.com/redirect/3ce2a0fc-2a94-42=
af-a959-66d0ee93c532?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
TL;DR: About 300 years ago, we discovered ancient scrolls (Herculaneum Papy=
ri)  from the library of Julius Ceasar=E2=80=99s father-in-law=E2=80=99s vi=
lla (79 AD). The scrolls were carbonized by volcanic heat, but preserved. T=
hey=E2=80=99re currently too delicate to unroll, but if we were able to rea=
d them it would double the corpus of literature we have from antiquity.
A team of researchers recently developed a method called =E2=80=9Cvirtual u=
nwrapping=E2=80=9D that digitally unrolls and reads the scroll without phys=
ically opening it.=20
Now, a team led by Nat Friedman and Daniel Gross open sourcing the challeng=
e [ https://substack.com/redirect/3ce2a0fc-2a94-42af-a959-66d0ee93c532?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] to read th=
e Herculaneum Papyri. After 275 years, the ancient puzzle of the Herculaneu=
m Papyri has been reduced to a software problem. The prize is $250K and the=
 bragging rights that come with unlocking the wisdom of antiquity.
(4) Drugs in Orbit: One Startup=E2=80=99s Big Idea for Microgravity [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/af29af94-b2e3-484f-acac-4509b78208c2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Ashlee Vance [ https://substack.com/redirect/c54dd0b4-97dc-4e46-92be-37c55b=
7813f0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
 for Bloomberg
Numerous promising drugs can crystallize when stored, rendering them unusab=
le on humans. Infamously, this issue forced a stop to the sales of the pill=
 form of the HIV drug Ritonavir in the late 1990s, after years of research =
and hundreds of millions of dollars in investment. Varda=E2=80=99s executiv=
es think the company can use orbital labs to kick-start development of new =
versions of many older drugs in safe pill and injectable forms.
It=E2=80=99s been a good week for atoms, too! On Wednesday, Not Boring Capi=
tal portfolio company Varda [ https://substack.com/redirect/05c51ed3-b568-4=
2f1-8571-1897c48856b6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ] announced [ https://substack.com/redirect/d9cc1cb3-d124-403=
9-ab5c-f62f8ef93c3c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU ] that it =E2=80=9Chas been awarded a $60m Air Force STRATFI co=
ntract to advance our nation=E2=80=99s hypersonic capabilities.=E2=80=9D Va=
rda manufactures things in space and then sends them back to earth in a re-=
entry vehicle; the Air Force will use that re-entry vehicle as a test-bed f=
or hypersonics during the return trip. =F0=9F=87=BA=F0=9F=87=B8
The same day, Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Ashlee Vance wrote a piece unveiling exac=
tly what it is that Varda will be manufacturing up there: drugs. Specifical=
ly, Varda can take advantage of microgravity to develop small molecule phar=
maceuticals that can=E2=80=99t be made on Earth, starting with the HIV drug=
 Ritonavir.=20
Biotech in space. Things are going to keep getting crazier at the intersect=
ions.
(5) Zipline [ https://substack.com/redirect/700cc5eb-e65f-4c8f-acee-8bba95b=
56d76?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Speaking of flying things, Zipline unveiled it=E2=80=99s new drone-powered =
delivery system that aims to reduce the carbon footprint of delivery logist=
ics and deliver on a decades-old promise of drone delivery. The company has=
 been around for a while now and is already executing thousands of deliveri=
es per day, but this is the most public showing of its future plans. Ziplin=
e is, of course, not the first company to take on the drone delivery challe=
nge. Amazon has likely invested billions of dollars into the project, and b=
een stymied by a mix of infeasibility and government regulation.
Zipline=E2=80=99s approach =E2=80=94 clean, quiet, faster, safe, integrated=
 =E2=80=94 seems like a good one. We are not in a position to say whether o=
r not Zipline will be successful, but we are rooting for more cleaner, fast=
er, and cheaper delivery options. There=E2=80=99s enough volume to go aroun=
d for everybody. It=E2=80=99s why we backed Pipedream [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/cd753fce-fec6-44c3-a98c-91dc0e897601?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Here=E2=80=99s to a future in wh=
ich Zipline dominates the skies, while Pipedream rules the earth.
